{"cursor":"3688","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox artist |name =Lajos Vajda |image=Vajda_Lajos_SzentendrÃ©n,_1939.jpg\n|caption=Vajda Lajos in Szentendre (1939) |birth_date= 6 August 1908\n|birth_place=Zalaegerszeg |death_date=7 September 1941 |death_place=Budakeszi\n|nationality=Hungarian |movement=Avant-garde |bgcolour=#69A0F3 }}\n\nHungarian Painter. (1908, Zalaegerszeg - 1941, Budakeszi)\n\nHe was a student of IstvÃ¡n CsÃ³k at the Hungarian Academy of Fine Arts in 1927-\n30. He studied together with DezsÃµ Korniss at Fernand LÃ©ger in Paris in 1930-34\nwhere he was introduced to cubism and surrealism.\n\nHe lived and worked in Szentendre, Hungary. Following the method of composers\nBÃ©la BartÃ³k and ZoltÃ¡n KodÃ¡ly he collected folk art motifs in Szentendre and\nSzigetmonostor for his artworks.\n\nHe combined religious (orthodox christian, roman catholic and jewish) symbols,\narchitectural and folk art motifs, abstract, figurative, and surrealistic\nelements on his pictures to create complex visionary images. His last abstract\nsurreal drawings foreshadow the horrors of World War II. He died of\ntuberculosis in 1941.\n\nHe is considered to be the most distinctive of the Hungarian avant-garde\nmovement. His art influenced generations of Hungarian artists among them the\nmembers of the European School Art Group (established in 1945) and the Vajda\nLajos Studio (established in 1972).\n\nHis works can be found in museums and private collections, among them in the\nHungarian National Gallery in Budapest and in the Vajda Lajos Museum in\nSzentendre, Hungary.\n","linknr":170,"url":"Lajos_Vajda","recorded":1375072540,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Lajos_Vajda&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Lajos_Vajda&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org